The poets had business relations, for the most part, only with these managers, who bought, or rejected, their playa, and who accordingly were very influentia] in determining the fate, and encouraging the development, of poetic taleni. In exceptional cases, however, the givers of the games, as they were men of experience in such matters and naturally felt great interest in the success of the performances, had a voice in the selection of the plays to be presented. All financial risk attending the presentation of a play was borne by the theatrica] manager. As it was of great importancc to the givers of the gamas that the people should be pleased with the amusements provided for them at such great ex- pense, a reward was offered to the dominas, varying in amount according to the success of the play given by him.1 This of course was calculated to secure the choico of the best possible play and to assure its presentation in the best possible manner. The dominas on his part was aooustomed, after a successful performance, to reward the deserving actors of his company with a banquet. cf. Plaut. cist. 7853 Bcd. 1418 ff. .

28. As regards the external equipment necessary for the dramatic performances, this was provided by contractors (coaductores; cf. Plaut. Asia. Prol. 3), under the super- vision of those who gave the games.²
